The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former Solidarity leader, former political prisoner and former Foreign Affairs Minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another statement claiming he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's conduct and Geremek stated that the law on decommunization constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional tribunal decision on May 11 largely invalidated the decommunization law, allowing Geremek to retain his European Parliament seat, at least for now.
But this law is part of a general policy by the Polish government whose sole aim is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a fight for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is the emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses his best, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into the underground when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroïka" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of revanchists from the post-Solidarity era, provincial disrupters from the post-communist period, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One sees everywhere alarming signs: the authority of the judiciary is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is questioned, civil servants are bought, and the role of prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and its losers.
The Polish revolution brought about public freedoms, but also more crime, a market economy but also the risk of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but also induced fear of the foreigner and fear of an invasion of mass Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison-like world, people were considered as belonging to the state, but the state took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous activists of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Thus, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against former enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be redressed.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to the first estimates, the lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised to lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and banned from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal Dziwisz of Kraków reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects—whether proven or not—for having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had taken place in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would be neither a member of NATO nor of the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge is fighting the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czesław Miłosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional tribunal offers hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the will for freedom, or what it generated, a democratic state.
